li.p:
 We find that \vvec_1=\twovec{1}{-2} is an
	eigenvector with associated eigenvalue \lambda_1=2 as
	is \vvec_2=\twovec{2}{1} with associated eigenvalue
	\lambda_2=-3.  Therefore, we have A=PDP^{-1}
	where

	  P = \mattwo12{-1}1, D=\mattwo200{-3}\text{.}

 If A=PBP^{-1}, then

	  \begin{aligned}
	  \det(A-\lambda I) \amp = \det(PBP^{-1}-\lambda PP^{-1}) \\
	  \amp = \det[P(B-\lambda I)P^{-1}] \\
	  \amp = \det(B-\lambda I)\text{.} \\
	  \end{aligned}

 If A=PBP^{-1}, then

	  \begin{aligned}
	  \det(A-\lambda I) \amp = \det(PBP^{-1}-\lambda PP^{-1}) \\
	  \amp = \det[P(B-\lambda I)P^{-1}] \\
	  \amp = \det(B-\lambda I)\text{.} \\
	  \end{aligned}
